{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608749/1958041501/1146.xml":{"full_text":"DAVID LAWRENCE\nPolitics and the Recession\nRevival of Democrats' Tactics of 3Os\nSeen in Taking of Truman Testimony\nThe Democrats apparently\nhave decided to make politi\ncal capital out of the reces\nsion. They are putting on\nhearings which are more con\ncerned with making political\npropaganda than with help\ning to put America\u2019s economic\nhouse In order.\nThe spectacle of taking\ntestimony from Harry Tru\nman. whose administration\nhas been accused of gross in\ndifference to c unemployment\nin the 1949 recession, is a\nkind of political circus which\nawakens memories of similar\ntactics in the 19305.\nFor the people of the\nUnited States are again pay\ning the penalty today of a\ndivided government. With\nthe Democrats in control of\nthe House from December,\n1930, through February, 1933.\nthe political warfare against\nthe Republican President in\nthe White House grew so in\ntense that the latter once\nremarked it was tragic to\nfind his opponents preferring\nto \u201cplay politics with human\nmisery.\u201d\nFor almost four years now\nthe Democratic Party has\nhad the major responsibility\nIn Congress, while the White\nHouse has been occupied by\na Republican President.\nWhen recessions come and\nnational unity is so essential\nto economic recovery, why is\nIt so important for the parti\nsans to play politics?\nThus President Eisenhower\nhas just pleaded with Con\ngress to pass legislation,\nwhich he recommended on\nMarch 25 of this year, to pro\nvide a temporary continua\ntion of unemployment com\npensation benefits for work\ners who have exhausted their\nbenefits under State and\nFederal laws. The President\ndeclared on Sunday:\n\u201cI said at the same time that\nprompt action was neces\nsary to give these workers\nand their families \u2019a greater\nmeasure of security.\u2019 This is\nnot a matter of statistics or\nDORIS FLEESON\nNixon's Role in the Slump\nVice President Found on the Outside\nAs President Turns to Businessmen\nThe President has not ac\ncepted Vice President Nixon\u2019s\npolitical judgment about the\nrecession, though It Is a\nJudgment with which many\nGovernment economists, past\nand present, agree. Mr. Nix\non will. In fact, be in South\nAmerica as the White House\nand Congress move into the\nclinches on a tax cut and\nother proposed recession\ncures.\nThe President also has\nblandly knocked down sug\ngestions that he ought to\ngive the Vice President a\nposition productive of' real\nexecutive experience. It is an\nodd circumstance that Mr\nNixon has never spent a day\nin an executive office, but it\nis true.\nThe Vice President, who\nworks every day at politics,\nis thoroughly unhappy about\nthese developments, but he\ncan only bide his time. They,\nof course, deal heavy blows\nto the legend that he is at the\nheart of the governmental\nmachine, mastering its every\ndetail and wielding real\npower.\nIt would be difficult to sug\ngest decisions more lmpor\nDOROTHY THOMPSON\nRussians Creating an Aristocracy\nStudent Elite, of Proper Background,\nIs Groomed for Leadership Caste\n\"Living in Russia is like\nliving on another planet. I\ndon\u2019t believe any Westerner\ncan understand it.\u201d\nHie speaker, a young\nEuropean who recently left\nthe Soviet Union after study*\nlng two years in a Russian\nuniversity, is now in the\nUnited States. His family,\nworkers, originally of Rus\nsian origin, left Russia be\nfore the First World War;\nbut he has heard and spoken\nRussian since childhood,\nstudied it systematically and\nspeaks it fluently. He told me\nthat the teaching in Russia\nwas at least up to the stand\nards of any European uni\nversity.\n\"But the atmosphere is to\ntally different from any\nwhere else. I'm not sure I\ncan explain it. Russians\u2014\nstudents and workers\u2014who\nknow about everything going\non in the world, are never\ntheless isolated in a world ot\ntheir own, and even somehow\nisolated from each other.\nThere is no Intimacy of con\ntact, such as one finds even\nbetween casual acquaintances\nIn the West. People don't\ndiscuss personal affairs or\nbeliefs. In thd Western\nsense, one doesn\u2019t have\nfriends, and this is almost\nimpossible to imagine,\n\u2018Tve never been in Amer\nica before. But America is\nJust as I imagined It. It\ndoesn't seem strange. Russia\nwas as strange after two\nyears as It was on the day I\narrived\u2014or stranger.\"\n\u201cAre people afraid?\u201d I\nasked.\n\"Not as you imagine. They\nare adjusted to fear and don't\nrecognize it as such. There\nIs no open terror any more,\nbut everyone knows it could!\nreturn. They don\u2019t want ir\neconomic theory. It concerns\npeople\u2014human beings\u2014who\nneed, and should have, the\nassistance of their Govern\nment.\n\u201cI hope that the members\nof the Congress will move as\nswiftly as possible on this vi\ntal problem when they re\nturn to Washington. All of\nus ,ln Government have a\nspecial responsibility to act to\nalleviate the hardships which\nare being suffered, through no\nfault of their own. by these\nworkers and their families.\"\nBut what is Congress do\ning? It started out this week\nwith a show In which for\nmer President Truman was\ninvited to air his political\nviews. Mr. Truman has been\nmaking sarcastic comments\nabout President Eisenhower,\none of which aits that if he\nwere President: \u201cI would be\ndoing something. I wouldn\u2019t\nbe sitting still or playing\ngolf.\"\nTo this. Meade Alcorn. Re\npublican National Chairman,\nreplied, as follows:\n\u201cIn 1949, a serious eco\nnomic recession began in the\nspring and unemployment\ngrew through the summer\nand Into the winter. Presi\ndent Truman and the Na\ntion were told in November\nthat unemployment in the\nprevious month had mounted\nto 3,823,000 or 6.1 per cent of\nthe smaller working force of\nthat time.\n\u201cOn November 26, Presi\ndent Truman left Washing\nton for Key West, Fla., where\nhe spent 24 days. He return\ned to Washington on Decem\nber 21 and two days later\nleft on a holiday trip of a\nweek to Independence, Mo.\n\u201cThe recession meanwhile\ndeepened through the winter\nand into 1950. A peak was\nreached in February when\n4,828.000 or 7.8 per cent of\nthe working force was out of\nwork\u2014slightly more than the\n7.7 per cent who were unem\nployed in March, 1958.\n\u201cThat figure was an\nnounced in the first part of\ntant to the Republican future\nthan those being taken with\nrespect to the economic de\ncline. In the background of\nevery G. O. P. officeholder's\nthought* must be the Hoo\nver years and the great de\npression which led to so\nmany votes of no confidence\nin that party. _\nThe Vioe President, of\ncourse, has his own immedi\nate future in mind. He can\nand does to a measure dis\nsociate himself from Eisen\nhower positions, but he knows\nhe must run. if nominated,\non the Eisenhower record,\nexactly as Adlai Stevenson\nhad no choice in 1952 but to\nembrace Harry Truman. It\ndid not help Mr. Stevenson\nthat the embrace was grudg\ning: it may have hurt hjm.\nThe question arises why, in\na situation with such deeply\npolitical overtones, the Pres\nident does not give greater\nweight to Mr. Nixon, the pol\nitician. Repeatedly Mr. Eisen\nhower has praised Mr. Nix\non\u2019s capabilities and he has\nnever questioned his tech\nniques. Often the President\nhas seemed to abdicate the\nrole of leader of his party\nto return, and are there\nfore against anyone who, by\ngetting out of bounds, might\nbring it back. If it returned\nthey would not blame the\nsystem, but the culprits.\n\u2018\u2018Every student must work\nduring vacations, in a fac\ntory or on a farm. I found\nworkers more open in con\ntacts than students. But\nI never, in over two years,\nheard one single criticism\nof the system as such.\nThere\u2019s criticism of directors,\nmanagement, fellow workers,\nand even of professors, but\nit's always because they\naren't sufficiently helping the\nsystem to flourish.\n\"They have been told that\nSoviet socialism is the most\nadvanced society on earth,\nand believe it.\n\u201cThey have no doubt what\never about the future.\n\"During the lsst war they\nwere told that men and\nmorale would always win\neven against superior tech\nnology. Today, they are con\nvinced of their technological\nsuperiority also. Everywhere\nelse people are afraid of\nwar. In Russia they are not.\nThey don\u2019t want war, but\nwould accept it. You never\nhear \u2018No nation can win\nanother war.' They are abso\nlutely convinced they would\nwin it. Nowhere Is there such\nunqualified confidence of su\nperiority,\n\u201cDuring the Suea crisis,\nI heard only one criticism:\n'The government is not ac\ntive enough.' Students and\nworkers struck fists on a\ntable an<f cried, 'What are\nwe waiting for! Let them\nhave It!\u201d\u2019\nI asked further about the\ndifference between students\nand workers.\n\"University and technical\nstudents go through the\nMarch, 1950. On March 13.\nPresident Truman again left\nWashington for Key West\nwhere he spent 29 days. The\nlatter trip was taken shortly\nafter Mr. Truman said In an\ninterview that up to 5 million\nunemployed was \u2019supportable\u2019\nand it was \u2018healthy for the\neconomic body\u2019 if job-seek\ning went on at all times.\u201d\nThe Federal Reserve Board\nhas just announced that in\ndustrial production in March\nof this year was 28 per cent\nabove the 1947-1949 average.\nThis was during the Truman\nrecession.\nMr. Truman was asked at\nthe hearing here this week\nby Representative Henry O.\nTalle of lowa, Republican,\nif he said in an Interview in\nthe New York Times in 1950\nthat unemployment of three\nto five million persons would\nnot be too bad a thing. The\nformer President denied that\nhe said it. whereupon Arthur\nKrock of the New York\nTimes, who had obtained the\ninterview, issued a statement\nsaying that Mr. Truman pro\nposed the Interview to him\nand that the manuscript was\nsubmitted to the White House\nand was returned to the\nTimes in the form in which\nit was printed. Mr. Krock\nalso says that in the press\nconference at the White\nHouse the next day. Mr.\nTruman was asked it the\ninterview was authorized in\nthe form in which it ap\npeared and he answered:\n\u201cIt was.\"\nMeade Alcorn says the\nformer President possesses\n\u201ca rather convenient memory\nof events in his administra\ntion.\"\nThat\u2019s what is going on in\nWashington in time of re\ncession\u2014the partisan clamor\nis just as it was in the 1930 s\nwhen the Government was\ndivided between two political\nparties. It deepened the\ndepression and prevented\nrecovery in America even\nthough a world-wide recovery\nmovement was under way in\n1932.\n(aeproduction RlthU Ruervcd)\nto the young Vice President,\nwho likes it and devotes tire\nless energy and skill to it.\nThe answer seems to be\nthat the President looks upon\nthe recession purely as a busi\nness problem and has turned\nto businessmen for the an\nswers. Congress understands\nthat the most effective single\nvoice at the White House on\nthis issue is that of former\nTreasury Secretary Hum\nphrey.\nThe President's Council of\nEconomic Advisers supports a\ntax cut. So does its former\nchairman, Arthur Bums, in\nwhom the President once had\ngreat faith.\nOne politician determined\nto handle the recession issue\nwith due regard for its cutting\nedge everywhere is Harry\nTruman. He was sorely\ntempted to spar with some of\nhis pet enemies on Capitol\nHill, the conservative Repub\nlicans of the House Ways and\nMeans Committee, but he re-\u00bb\nslated temptation.\nInstead, he read a sober doc\nument. written with the help\nof what he called \"my smart\nest friends.\u201d and he refused\nto stray far afield from it.\nHe wanted the stories on his\ntestimony to deal with his\nproposals, not his politics,\nand he arranged it that way.\nmost rigorous selective proc\ness Imaginable. They are the\nleadership caste, and more\nwill be required of them than\nof others.\n\"Even their family back\ngrounds are scrutinized. Are\nthere any counts against the\nfather for absenteeism or\nother misdemeanors? Is he\na party member, and if so\nhow active in performing\nparty duties? What Is the\napplicant's school record? He\nmust have been a brilliant\nand industrious student, but\nthat is not enough. Was he\nan active member of the\nKomsomol? Was he a leader\nand Instructor of younger\nboys, and as such kind, firm\nand well liked?\n\"Even his looks, manners,\nand dress count. He must be\ncourteous, neat, and if nat\nurally handsome so much the\nbetter, especially if he is\nbeing educated for a mission\nabroad. Russia is creating\nan aristocracy as consciously\nas the British Empire did in\nEton and Oxford.\n\"And like members of that\naristocracy, he must be re\nserved, not show emotions,\nexpress personal feelings, or\ncare about money.\u201d\n\"Some of these lads must\nhave \u2018prill,\u2019\" I suggested.\n\"Yes; I\u2019ve heard it talked\nabout. But it isn\u2019t wide\nspread. It's too dangerous\nfor protector and protege.\nThe sort of thing that the\npress would expose and de\nnounce.\u201d\n\"Were you a good stu\ndent?\u201d\n\"Yes.\u201d\n\u201cMight you have become a\nSoviet citizen and entered\nthis 'elite'?\"\n\"Probably.\"\n\"Have you thought of do\ning so?\u201d\n\"No. It\u2019s like living on an\nother planet. You have to ba,\nConditioned.\u201d O\n(Helmed b\u00bb the Bell Syndicate. lac'\nLOUIE\n\nPOTOMAC FEVER\nFLCTCHCR KNEBCL\nIke throws out the first baseball of the season. This\npresidential chore resembles the state-of-the-Union mes\nsage. After each, everybody asks: \u201cWho\u2019s on first?\u201d\n\nHarry Truman urges a (5 billion tax cut for low and\nmiddle incomes. Harry figures the rich don\u2019t need help.\nThey either wind up as Republicans\u2014or Democratic candi\ndates for President.\n\nNews from the allied mountain-climbing club: John\nFoster Dulles is in fine shape as he approaches the summit\n\u2014but fatigue is noted among the horses which have been\ndragging him.\n\nEconomists\u2019 recession jargon: \u201cTo bottom out\u201d\u2014a run\nner tagged out sliding into third.\n\nUnited States Senate: The last free forum of debate where\nSenators can practice up for the week-end TV panel shows.\n\nLabor Secretary Mitchell says we have a basically sound\neconomy. In fact, the more soundings the Eisenhower team\ntakes, the more basic it gets.\nVerdict Clears\nDetective Agent\nA Federal court Jury here\nyesterday returned a not guilty\nverdict after considering per\njury charges against Leo D.\nMalone, former special police\nman.\nMalone. 37, of the 200 block\nof W street N.W. had been\ncharged with lying at a Munic\nipal Court trial last July about\nhis participation in a die*- same.\nHe was also charged with in\nducing two witnesses to lie\nabout it.\nAs a result of the Municipal\nCourt trial. Malone was con\nvicted of shooting dice and\npaid a fine of $25. His attor\nney in the District Court per\njury trial yesterday was Rich\nard D. Gibbs. Mtione was an\nagent for the National Detec\ntive Agency here from April to\nNovember. 1932.\nL\nCgdNH? ks M y yjr Only on Broniff eon you enjoy\u2014\nDORADO, DC-7C, tho faitott, largo*!, most\nU modern airlinor to link the US.A. and South America\nDeluxe HrtAclau\u2014no oxtra tore\u2014-end excellent\njPMf l low-cost lour it! accommodation* to\n_ vV Jf M PANAMA UMA SAO PAULO \u2022WO\nii mkmm MEW EL CONQUBTADO*. Potior liner. 4-ongino\nDC-6 flight* between the US A. and 9 Latin American\ncountries Mottor-ehol meals and Bronifft\nfinest, most luxurious to W\nsounpnm\nboth first-class and MOW I Through service to\ntourist accommodations BMB ES Q QTA\non all flights I\nI Three deluxe NEW El Conquittodor flight* weekly,\nI Miami, Panama VV i***i\u00bb*\u00ab*\u00a3\u00a3h\nWashington and Bogota.\nPhono your travel ogont, or,\nBroniff Intornotionol Airway*:\nStarting 3-3220 f attorn Air lines:\nLINKING THE AMERICAS\nCe\u00abBsga\u00bbsssaa\u00df\u00dfa\u00df\u00df\u00df\u00dfSS\u00dfa\u00abgaT'.v; l \\rf.''in?;Trffi\u00dfsa\u00bb )^y'^^\nBRANIFF (f EASTERN\nI WTIW WSTIONSt SISWSYI J// AIItI. IN JJ\n\u2014By Harry Hanon\n[ii\nM\n1\nera. emmm,\nCounts Dismissed\nAgainst Lawyers\nFederal Judge Bolitha J. Law?\nyesterday dismissed two counts\nof obstructing Justice against\ni Washington Attorney Howard\nD. Levine.\nThe lawyer last month re\nceived a suspended sentence of\nfour months to a year and a\nday after his conviction of\nfalsely himself as\na police officer.\nAssistant United States At\ntorney Victor Caputy moved\nyesterday to have the other\ncharges dismissed in light of\nlast month's conviction.\nHeads Birdbanders\nRAMSEY, N. J.. April 15. UPt.\nSeth Low of the United States\nFish and Wildlife Service.\nLaurel. Md.. has been elected\ni president of the Eastern Bird\nbanding Association.\nCONSTANTINE BROWN\na, i n\nSuspicion of a Summit Parley\nGrass Roots Reported Fearing Trap\nAnd Opposing 'Peace at Any Price'\nState Department liaison\nofficers with Congress are\nbird-dogging the sentiments\nof the grass roots toward such\nquestions as foreign economic\naid, the summit meeting and\nreciprocal trade agreements.\nThe reports of members of\nCongress who have just re\nturned from fact finding\ntours during the Easter recess\nIn their Btates and districts\nIndicate increasing hostility\nto indiscriminate economic\nand military aid. There is,\nhowever, a sentiment favor\ning limited economic assist\nance, and effective military\naid to the nations whldh have,\nproved loyal to America. Ac\ncording to some legislators\nthe \u201cbig tent\u201d show organ\nized under the direction of\nEric Johnston has done more\nharm than good to the advo\ncates of the near-$4 billion\nprogram for the 1959 fiscal\nyear.\nThere is some confusion\nconcerning the five-year ex\ntension of executive powers\nfor trade agreements. In\nsome areas where American\nindustry has been hard hit\nby foreign competition there\nis. of course, a marked hos\ntility to any tariff reduction.\nThis is particularly notice\nable, according to the return\ning legislators, on the West\nCoast and in New England,\nwhere many American work\ners feel they have become\nunemployed as a result of\nforeign competition.\nThe administration\u2019s ar\ngument that some three mil\nlion workers are emplqyed\nproducing goods for export\nis contradicted. It is pointed\nout that a larger number of\nworkers may become unem\nployed as a result of lower\ning duties on competitive\ngoods produced abroad.\nThe reaction of the grass\nroots to the summit confer\nence is interesting if the\nmembers of Congress have\ngauged accurately their peo\nples' reactions. Except in\nsome \"intellectual circles\u201d\ninspired by ideologists, there\nis a deep suspicion that we\nmay get the short end of\nthe stick if President Elsen\nhower agrees to meet Prime\nMinister Khrushchev on the\nlatter\u2019s terms to sit down\ntogether and cover the water\nfront. The wish for peace\ncontinues to be strong; so\nare the misgivings eoncern\nTHE EVENING STAR. Washington, D. C.\nTuesday, Aran, is. i\u00bbsa\ning a nuclear war. But, by\nand large, the reported sen\ntiment of the American peo\nple seems to be against\n\u201cpeace at any price.\u201d\nThe decision to attend a\nsummit meeting belongs to\nPresident Eisenhower alone.\nCongress has nothing to say\nabout it. There was a thought\non the part of a number of\nSenators earlier this year to\noffer a \u201csense of the Senate\u201d\nresolution opposing the Rus\nsian summit plan. Even if\nit were passed with a sub\nstantial majority (and this\nseems doubtful) it would not\nhave been binding on the\nExecutive.\nThe Soviet propaganda has\nattempted to make out that\nonly such a conference be\ntween Messrs. Eisenhower and\nKhrushchev, the heads of the\nremaining two great powers\n(the Prime Ministers of Brit\nain and France would be\nmerely tolerated) could bring\nabout such peace in the\nworld. Some of President\nEisenhower\u2019s political friends\nwho frown at the idea of a\nmeeting on Mr. Khrushchev\u2019s\nterms have drawn his atten\ntion to the historical speech\nmade by President Woodrow\nWilson on February 11, 1913:\n\u201cWe cannot have a general\npeace for the asking or by\nmere arrangements at a con\nference. Peace cannot be\npieced together out of indi\nvidual understandings be\ntween powerful states.\u201d\nThis is exactly what Prime\nMinister Khrushchev is press\ning us to do. He has said in\nhis public utterances and pri\nvately at the various vodka\nand caviar functions in Mos\ncow that the end of the cold\nwar and the road to peace\nKNO FINER, FRESHER\nmCQFFEE AVAILABLE v%lKgk\n\u25a0A java MOCHA GUATEMALA BLEND\na blend of very smooth, rich, flavored I\ncoffees and Tull bodied, winey flavored 88/rfm\nGuatemala. An M. E. Swing f|F ik /V/\na\u00b0m Sl.ua lb\nFour other custom blends \\XtW A\nto choose\n1013 E ST. N.W. Phone NA. 8-7601 'jM\nAll Coffer Xocstrd on Premises\n\ndepend on a meeting with\nAmerica\u2019s Chief Executive.\nThe point of view advo\ncated by Secretary Dulles, the\nadministration\u2019s principal\nspokesman on international\naffairs, is that peace cannot\nbe obtained by a mere vague\nunderstanding between Amer\nica and the Soviet Union.\nPeace is a collective matter\nin which the rights of peoples\nof the big and small coun\ntries must be considered.\nThese sound, thoughts were\ntranslated in the answers to\nthe Bulganin and Khru\nshchev letters. Washington\nsuggested that before the\nheads of states meet, there\nmust be a preliminary agree\nment on the \u201csubstantive\nmatters\u201d which are respon\nsible for the present world\ntensions. Mere expressions of\nlasting friendship, we told\nthe Russians, will not bring\neven a temporary relief as\nlong as the present cancers\nremain and continue to grow\nin the international body.\nThe Russian dictator has\nso far turned down this logi\ncal approach, which alone\ncan make a summit confer\nence effective. Mr. Khru\nshchev wants a \"summit\nparty\u201d and not a conference.\nBut there is no question that\nhe will continue to press us\nfor it with all the means\nat his disposal.\nAdministration scouts were\nsurprised to hear that in\nmany parts of the country\nvarious Republican and\nDemocratic clubs and study\ngroups are getting themselves\nInformed about the mean\ning of this \u201csummit confer\nence.\u201d Speakers are being in\nvited to explain the meaning\nof such a gathering. They\nwere equally surprised to find\nthat the over-all opinion is\nadverse to holding a confer\nence on Russia\u2019s terms.\nA-13","height":"28572","width":"18337"}}
